\begin_layout Standard
The "Fast Mode" switch enables some optimizations in the IO code in order
 to improve calculation times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Force Pressure-Enthalpy (PH) Flash calculations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If enabled, all requests by unit operations for PT Flashes will be replaced
 by PH ones.
 This option must be activated if you are working with only one component
 (steam simulation, for example), otherwise you won't have partial vaporization/
liquefaction in valves, compressors and expanders, if that is the case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Calculate Bubble and Dew points at stream conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Check this box if you want the DWSIM to calculate bubble and dew points
 at conditions specified on each material stream.
 The calculated values will be shown only if the stream is at VLE equilibrium.
 The calculations are not exactly fast, so use this option with caution
 and only if needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Validate Equilibrium Flash Calculation Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If enabled, DWSIM will check the mixture Gibbs energy before and after the
 equilibrium flash calculation.
 If the gibbs energy 
\emph on
increases
\emph default
 after the calculation (it should always 
\emph on
decrease
\emph default
 when there is a phase split), an error message will be shown and the flowsheet
 calculation will be aborted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Apply a Phase Identification Algorithm after Equilibrium Calculations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Check this to apply an identification algorithm to each phase after the
 equilibrium calculation is finished.
 This can be useful for supercritical compounds which behave as liquid at
 high pressures and temperatures, or special mixtures which exhibit LLE
 behavior at low temperatures, incorrectly identified as VLE by the flash
 algorithms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
This procedure is enabled by default and will override the flash result
 regarding phase identification
\series default
.
 For instance, the result of a flash calculation may give an all-vapor solution
 and, after the phase identification algorithm is applied, the phase may,
 in fact, behave as liquid.
 In this case, DWSIM will show this phase as liquid in the Material Stream
 property window.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visit DWSIM's wiki for more information about the phase identification algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Stability Test
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a flash algorithm with a three-phase capability is selected, DWSIM
 needs to know which components are most likely to be present in a second
 liquid phase.
 You can do that by selecting the ones you think that will be in a higher
 amount - that is, the key components for the second liquid phase.
 That doesn't necessarily imposes that the other, unselected components
 cannot be present in the second liquid phase - only the equilibrium calculation
 will tell you that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The search severity setting controls how much effort DWSIM should put into
 searching for a second liquid phase.
 In the 
\emph on
Low
\emph default
 setting, only one trial phase is created with a mixture of the key components
 and the convergence tolerance is somewhat high.
 In the 
\emph on
High
\emph default
 setting, DWSIM will include additional trial phases, one for each key component
 and do additional checks using incipient phases' gibbs energy, with the
 smallest convergence tolerance value (1E-06).
 
\end_layout

